Puzzle 

Guess Color of Hat

There are 20 people standing in a line, one behind the other.

Each is made to wear a hat, which can be either white or black.
There can be any number of white or black hats between 0 and 20.
Each person can see the hats of all the people ahead of him in the line, but not those of the people standing behind.
Each person is required to guess (loudly) the colour of his/her own hat.
The objective is for the group to get as many correct guesses as possible.
The group is allowed to discuss and form a strategy before the exercise.
What is the best strategy? What is the maximum number of correct guesses in this strategy?

Solution:

There are 20 people standing in a queue, each wearing either a black or a white hat. No one can see their own hat, but each person can see the hats of all the people standing in front of them. The last person in the queue (the 20th person) can therefore see the hats of the 19 people ahead of him.

He counts the number of white hats among them.
If the number of white hats is even, he says "Black".
If the number of white hats is odd, he says "White".
His guess has a 50% chance of being correct, because he has no information about his own hat.
However, his guess encodes a message for those in front of him.
The 19th person hears the 20th person's guess and uses it as a clue about the parity (even or odd) of white hats among the first 19 people. He then counts the number of white hats in front of him—that is, among the first 18 people. If the number he sees is even and the 20th person announced “even,” he knows his own hat must be black; if the number he sees is odd, then his hat must be white. This allows him to determine his hat colour with certainty.

This strategy continues with each person in the queue. Each one uses the original parity announced by the 20th person, the colours of hats they see ahead, and the guesses already made to calculate their own hat colour. By tracking how the number of white hats changes based on the earlier guesses, they can adjust the parity and deduce the colour of their own hat without error.

As a result, the first 19 people in the queue (positions 1 to 19) can always guess their hat colour correctly. Only the 20th person, who has no information about their own hat and makes the initial parity announcement, may guess incorrectly, with a 50% chance of being right
